    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my aero exam and I'm a bit stuck on the lifting force. Can you explain Bernoulli's principle and how it specifically relates to the shape of an airfoil to create lift? Thanks.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! Bernoulli's principle is all about the relationship between the speed of a fluid and its pressure. In the case of an airfoil, the shape is designed to create a difference in airspeed above and below the wing. The upper surface is curved, which causes the air to move faster over the top, reducing the pressure there. Meanwhile, the lower surface is flatter, slowing the air down and increasing the pressure. This pressure difference creates lift, as the higher pressure below the wing pushes the wing up. It's a bit like how a bird can fly—its wings are shaped to create this pressure difference, allowing it to lift off the ground.",
      "source": "target",
