    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but I'm getting some confused looking at my textbook. Some parts mention things about the Coanda effect and how the air \"sticks\" to the curve of the wing. How does that part work alongside Bernoulli's principle to actually make the lift happen? Is it one or the other?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the Coanda effect is another fascinating aspect of aerodynamics. It works hand in hand with Bernoulli's principle to create lift. When the air flows over the curved upper surface of the wing, it tends to follow the curve due to the Coanda effect, which is the tendency of a fluid jet to stay attached to a convex surface. This helps maintain the high-speed airflow over the top of the wing, contributing to the lower pressure area. So, it's not one or the other; it's more like a team effort. The Coanda effect helps to sustain the airflow pattern that Bernoulli's principle helps to create, making sure that the pressure difference between the top and bottom surfaces of the wing remains strong enough to generate lift. Think of it like a group of friends holding hands in a circle—it's their combined effort that keeps the circle together, just like the Coanda effect and Bernoulli's principle work together to keep the wing lifting off the ground.",
      "source": "target",
