    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Okay, I get the teamwork part. But what happens if that airflow \"detaches\" or breaks away from the wing surface? My book says that causes a stall. Why does the air suddenly stop following the curve, and what does that actually do to the lift?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the dreaded stall! When the airflow on the wing's surface separates or \"detaches,\" it's like a group of friends losing their grip on each other. The smooth, attached airflow that helps create the pressure difference needed for lift is disrupted. This happens when the angle of attack—the angle between the wing and the oncoming air—becomes too steep. The air can't follow the curve of the wing anymore, and the pressure difference that creates lift diminishes. As a result, the wing loses lift and can even fall if the airflow completely separates from the wing surface. It's a bit like trying to walk on a path that suddenly ends; you can't continue moving forward without that path. In the case of an airplane, a stall can be dangerous because it might lead to a loss of control. So, pilots need to be careful not to exceed the critical angle of attack where the airflow detaches.",
      "source": "target",
